››››                              The Fish›››     This is a  report on the basic anatomy of the fish, specifically the Yellow Perch.››     The Yellow Perch is of the animal kingcom, chordata phylum, this meaning it has a spine. The class is pisces.››     The Yellow Perch is a true fish or bony fish, meaning it has a skeleton of bone instead of cartilage. Bony fishes are today the most dominant vertabrates in the marine environment.››     Fish are animals that are ideally adapted for aquatic life. It has gills for underwater respiration. The body is tapered at both ends for a streamlined shape to move easily through the water. The body is covered with scales. Scales are thin flat discs of bone that overlap each other like roof shingles. As a fish grows the scales grow but always stay the same in numbers.››     Skin glands secrete a mucus that seeps between the scales forming a cover of lubrication that helps the fish glide through the water easier and also adds a protection against enemies and parasitic fungi, bacteria, and protozoans.››     Many fish are colored. Coloring aids in protection because it camouflages the fish. Most fish are dark on top in order to blend in with the bottom when viewed from above and light on the bottom to blend with the bright light near the surface.››     Fish have fins. Fins are thin membranes supported by rays and spines that aid it in swimming. Rays spread the fin out like a fan and spines are for defense.››     There are two sets of paired fins. The pectoral fins nearest the head and the ventral fins posterior and below the pectoral fins. These fins act like oars when it swims slowly and help it steer and keep its balance. They also help it move backwards. Next there are single fins:›     The caudal fin on the tail which makes it move foreward.›     The anterior and posterior dorsal fins that help the fish to stay upright when swimming.›     The anal fin on the ventral side also helps it to keep its balance.››     Now we'll focus on the special organs. The respiratory system on the fish is what exchanges gasses underwater. It consists of four gills in each of two gill chambers on each side of its body. The gill is made of an arched bone fringed with a double row of gill filaments. The gill filaments are full of capillaries which bring the blood in close contact with the water. On the gills near the throat are fingerlike projections called gill rakers which prevent food and debris from getting into the gills and slowing down the movement of water over them.››     Next is the circulatory system which delivers blood carrying oxygen and nutrients and removes carbon dioxide and other wastes. The blood flows in a single circuit from the body into the sinuous venosis which holds the blood before entering the heart and increases the blood pressure a little. Next it flows into the atrium, a thin muscular walled chamber of the heart where the blood pressure is increased even more. From here it flows into the ventricle, a thick-walled, highly muscular pump of the heart, where blood pressure is increased even more. It then flows into a really elastic structure called the bulbus arteriosus which makes the blood flow in a steady stream instead of in spurts. This helps get gases out of the blood better. From here it goes to the gills where gases are exchanged and then the blood goes to the body. From there it begins the circuit all over again.››The digestive system of the Yellow Perch is fairly simple. It has a large mouth on its anterior end. The mouth has a special hinge to allow it to open its mouth wide to swallow big bites. Since the Yellow Perch is carnivorous (meat eating) it has many sharp teeth.The teeth point backwards for easier swallowing but it also makes it harder for food to come back out. It also has a tongue. The tongue can't move butis covered with taste buds that allow it to taste and detect chemicals in the water. After the food leaves the mouth it enters the pharynx or throat cavity. From here it enters the rather short esophogus which in turn is connected to the stomach. The esophagus and stomach are in a straight line with each other so it can swallow large prey. Next to the stomach are the large, well-developed liver and smaller, hard to find pancreas which secrete digestive enzymes. The end of the stomach is a rather short intestine. At this place little fingerlike projections stick out called pyloric caeca. Pyloric caeca do a considerable omount of food digestion and absorption. Digestion still occurs as food moves down the intestine. Undigested food leaves through the anus.››      The excretory system in fish has adapted to underwater life. As you know waste gasses leave the body through the gills. Solid wastes are removed from the blood by the kidneys. Ducts lead from the kidneys to the urinary bladder where they arre later discharged. Kidneyx of the fish maintain a water and salt balance in the aquatic environment.››     Reproduction organs in the fish are called gonads. In the female they are called ovaries. Ovaries produce eggs when the fish is mature. In the male, the gonads are calles testes which produce sperm cells. When the female lays her eggs the male swims over the eggs and fertilizes them. Fertilization occurs outside the body. The eggs develop into embryos and continue to grow into little fishies and their life process starts all over again.››     Fish are very economically important. They provide food for people. They eat bugs and stuff out of our lakes and streams. They provide biological specimens for study for the nations youth.››                              THE END